comments.body:
> @copilot i think the goal is to also animate to a position. So actually play. Can you think of a good way to do this. 

Added `PlayToFrame`, `PlayToProgress`, and `PlayToTime` in commit `2daa73d`. These drive the animation timer naturally to a target, auto-detecting whether to play forward or backward:

```csharp
// Toggle switch: animates forward on open, backward on close
lottieView.PlayToFrame(isOn ? lottieView.FrameCount - 1 : 0);

// Animate to the 50% position
lottieView.PlayToProgress(0.5);

// Animate to a specific time
lottieView.PlayToTime(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(1.5));
```

Key design choices:
- Direction (forward/backward) is auto-detected by comparing `target` to `Progress`
- Speed respects `AnimationSpeed`'s magnitude (e.g. 2x speed = twice as fast)
- `AnimationCompleted` is **not** fired when `PlayTo` stops at the target — that event remains for natural playback completion only
- Calling any `SeekTo*` method or loading a new source cancels a running `PlayTo`

The sample app also has "Play→0%", "Play→50%", "Play→100%" buttons to demonstrate the animated seeking.
